Response:
In some of the questions with sentences my answers were more nuanced than the options given. 

Thank you for the work you are doing. I hope my data has been helpful. I have Aspergers.

GL with the data and getting the paper published!

The first list of questions could have had more options rather than one completely disagree vs. three that say agree: now and when I was younger (or just now or just when I was younger). As a kid I don't really thought about other people / making friends because my twin sister was always there with me. So I kinda could go with the flow and watch her initiate all contacts. Realizing social skills wasn't my strongsuit came in my late teens. Once I had myself tested they diagnosed Asperger. A lot of my social skills are copied behaviour rather than naturally inclined.
This was far too long. It felt like it would never end

Thank you for the opportunity to take part in this four part study.

On the first part, I would say that the animations featured manufactured observations of a 2D world that we, from the point of view of a 3D world can have no chance of comprehending. All movements were random and the shapes did not have any emotions. They were tirangles.

On the second parrt, there were, I think, three occasions when I didn't say I was certain of getting the answer correct. On each of these three occasions, I accidentally clicked the, 'Submit Answer,' button before moving the slider. Also, on reflection, I think that it may have been impossible to give a correct answer, at times, as I think the number of dots may have been identical. I don't know what you were testing for, but technology watching where participants looked before answering might have been useful.

On the third part: for the first sets of questions, I was asked if a statement was true. Every time, I answered, 'Not true.' This is because none of what I was being asked could be established as empirical fact. So, the closest correct answer was, 'Not true.' However, on later sections, I enjoyed the questions thrown in to make sure I was still paying attention.

On the fourth part, that was fun. Thanks!

You definitely need a "don't know" option for a lot of those; I found myself trying to do "best fit" with answers that I did not know the answers for and often guessing. Like, triangles don't have emotions! I understood they told a story but the emotions I wouldve said weren't there.

That was waaaayy too long, especially when there is no guarentee that you will get the incentive! I couldn't turn my computer off for 4 days for fear of loosing my progress on the first part with all the dots. As those who are autistic often have concentration difficulties, at least 50% having ADHD diagnosis too, concentrating on an exercise like that is really really hard, and will likely have an effect on your results. Many was I bored, the dots exercise was far too long.

Thank you for doing this study. I found that many of the tasks required intense concentration, and were pretty tiring, similarly to the tasks I did as part of my autism diagnostic assessment.

For studies using such tasks in future, i think it would be worth warning people in the call for participants and information sheet that the tasks could require a lot of concentration and be very tiring. I was assuming I'd be answering a set of questions, whcih is what other studies publicised through Autistica often consist of, in my experience.

I was also surprised that so little information was provided in the Autistica callf for participants - just an email address to contact, without even a name attached. And the pre-screen questionnaire also gave very little info about the nature of the study. I had to wait to get access to the actual survey and embedded information sheet before getting any detail about what the study would entail, being able to withdrawn at any time, etc. While of course this info does need to be presented at that point, i'd have expected some of it also to have been communicated earlier in the process of engaging with this research.

Thank you for considering my comments.

I had a problem with my browser at the start. The first set of animations didn't show up, I think it was supposed to be triangles or squares interacting with one another. When I reloaded, I was bumped to the section with the dots, and then did the section with triangles. I am not sure if I missed something at the start.

1. I chose options in the dots challenge but couldn't tell you why one seemed more likely than the other. That's why most of them were marked as guesses.
2. I wasn't sure what "unusual experiences" meant in some of the questions towards the end. If it was referring to the experience of being autistic, then that is unusual but there's no right/wrong angle to it, so some of those questions didn't make a lot of sense to me.

thank you for doing this research!
as i have numerous eye issues (glaucoma, blepharitis, visual snow) it is very hard to do the 'dots in box' test as looking at the screen with such stark colour contrast was painful and i am sure i had visual 'distortions'.
i could only work out the puzzle questions by using pen and paper as i cannot 'hold' information in my head.

With the dots exercise, most of my answers were not consciously thought about. It's more instinctive than processed - it was difficult to define whether I was confident about my answers since I wasn't making an explicit choice, it was automatic. 
In the first round of the dots with feedback (red/green outline) I found that if I consciously tried to compare the two and went against my 'instinct', I was more often wrong.
This was fun and interesting!

Quite intense and some parts certainly more difficult than others.  Took much longer than the 45-60 minutes initially advised but still quite enjoyable overall!

Good luck with the research!
This took me a long time to complete. Many of the tasks were difficult (especially the one with the flashing dots) and frankly left me feeling really shitty about myself. :(
i found this all very difficult. The most difficult study I have every done on cognitive ability. I very ,uch am interested in the outcome.
The task where you have to say which had the most dots was too long :(

I experienced quite a few sound distractions when completing the moving dots section, and also the screen flickered on a couple of occassions. Just out of interest, with the moving dots section, did one box deliberately remain on the screen for the slightest fraction of a second longer than the other to give the illusion of it having more dots? I also found the triangles section a little confusing, but I guess that was a part of the test? Overall it was quite interesting though.
